h2. Symptoms

Building Crowd from the sources fails with the following error:

{noformat}
[ERROR] Failed to execute goal com.atlassian.maven.plugins:maven-amps-plugin:3.5-m9:copy-bundled-dependencies (default-copy-bundled-dependencies) on project crowd-rest-application-management: Unable to execute mojo: Error copying artifact from /Users/berrueta/scratch/atlassian/crowd/components/crowd-rest/crowd-rest-common/target/classes to /Users/berrueta/scratch/atlassian/crowd/components/crowd-rest/crowd-rest-application-management/target/classes/META-INF/lib/classes: /Users/berrueta/scratch/atlassian/crowd/components/crowd-rest/crowd-rest-common/target/classes (Is a directory) -> [Help 1]
{noformat}

h2. Steps to reproduce

# Checkout the Crowd sources, or otherwise do a {{mvn clean}}.
# {{mvn compile}}

h2. Notes

This only happens if building a goal <= {{test}} (e.g., {{compile}}). If building {{package}} or {{install}}, the build succeeds.

The encryption method description says:

{noformat}
For compatibility between Atlassian products you must use ATLASSIAN-SECURITY.
{noformat}

This is an oversimplification: it's only necessary if you plan to migrate a user database between Crowd and other Atlassian products, and not necessary for general use of a Crowd server.

Fix the documentation to make this clear.

The following warning occurs when try to update crowd.cfg.xml in Windows.

{noformat}2014-02-11 17:30:09,569 localhost-startStop-1 WARN [atlassian.config.xml.AbstractDom4jXmlConfigurationPersister] Unable to move D:\Home\Crowd\crowd.cfg.xml112217985837833036tmp to D:\Home\Crowd\crowd.cfg.xml. Falling back to non-atomic overwrite..{noformat}

As mentioned in this Confluence  bug report [CONF-15549|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONF-15549]:
{quote}
Atomic file updates seem to be reasonably close to impossible on Windows. We should suppress this warning message (as it's not something the admin can do anything about). 
{quote}

Our customer faces quite a big (sometimes large) performance problem when synchronizing their Confluence against their Crowd. A full sync (which sometimes happens although incremental sync is enabled) takes 400-600s on an idle, production-like (i.e. powerful) test system, and can take more than *an hour* in production.
During most of the time, there are no requests to crowd, and only one thread is using a CPU core (100%), there are no I/O waits.

Thread dumps show that the culprit is {{com.atlassian.crowd.directory.DbCachingRemoteChangeOperations.findUserMembershipForGroupChanges}}

This method shows a few weaknesses:
* {{contains}} lookups are performed that are O\(n\)
* {{~n}} lookups are performed, so we have O(n^2)
first example is internalMembers:
{code}
List<String> internalMembers = ...
...
for (String remoteUser : remoteUsers)
{
    if (!internalMembers.contains(remoteUser))
        usersToAdd.add(remoteUser);
}
{code}
second is remoteUsers:
{code}
... Collection<String> remoteUsers ...
...
remoteUsers = Collections2.transform(remoteUsers, IdentifierUtils.TO_LOWER_CASE);
...
for (String internalUser : internalMembers)
{
    if (!remoteUsers.contains(internalUser))
        usersToRemove.add(internalUser);
}
{code}
* the {{contains}} lookups are performed against a life view made with {{Collections2.transform}} resp. {{Lists.transform}}, although
** the documentation of {{Collections2.transform}} states that {quote}When a live view is not needed, it may be faster to copy the transformed collection and use the copy.{quote}
** the documentation of {{Lists.transform}} even states {quote}The function is applied lazily, invoked when needed. This is necessary for the returned list to be a view, but it means that the function will be applied many times for bulk operations like List.contains(java.lang.Object){quote}
** which is exactly what is done here
** so we are not only dealing with O(n^2) comparisons, but also with n^2 invocations of {{toLowerCase}}, while only n would be needed

So I did what Google suggests, copy both collections into HashSets and use them for both iteration and {{contains}} lookup.

Result:
On the above mentioned test system, the sync takes about *15* seconds (30 times speedup).

Patch is attached, it was taken from Confluence 5.1.5 (Crowd 2.6.2), but applies cleanly against Crowd 2.7.0 (Confluence 5.4.2), too.

By specifying the {{application.login.url.template}} property, you can allow parameters set by the RP to appear in the URL to which users are redirected to authenticate, using the OpenID 2.0 extension NS {{https://developer.atlassian.com/display/CROWDDEV/CrowdID+OpenID+extensions#CrowdIDOpenIDextensions-login-page-parameters}}.

For example, if CrowdID configuration includes
{noformat}
application.login.url.template=http://some.service.example/login?key=${key}
{noformat}
and if an OpenID {{checkid_setup}} request is received which includes parameters
{noformat}
openid.ns.ext1=https://developer.atlassian.com/display/CROWDDEV/CrowdID+OpenID+extensions#CrowdIDOpenIDextensions-login-page-parameters
openid.ext1.key=value
{noformat}
Then users requiring authentication will be redirected to {{http://some.service.example/login?key=value}}.

The key names specified in {{application.login.url.template}} may not contain ‘}’ but are otherwise unrestricted. Values are replaced having been escaped suitably for use as query parameter values. Parameters absent in the OpenID request are replaced with empty strings.

It should be remembered that the values replaced in the login URL template are controlled by the (potentially external) relaying parties and as not necessarily to be trusted.

After a user import, it would be beneficial if admins can force their users to change their passwords on the first login. There should be an option during the directory/csv import to force all users to change their password post import to the target directory

h3.Workaround:
# Identify the id of the target directory (for the import):
{code}
SELECT * FROM cwd_directory;
{code}
# Run this query to update the said attribute to "true", for all users:
{code}
UPDATE cwd_user_attribute SET attribute_value = 'true', attribute_lower_value = 'true' WHERE directory_id = <id> AND attribute_name = 'requiresPasswordChange';
{code}
Where <id> is the directory id from query #1
# Restart Crowd

The Crowd API should support true read-only access, such that permissioned IDs cannot authenticate users and especially not retrieve session IDs without supplying passwords.

{quote}
Changing the user's password or deleting the user is an intrusive operation that will leave the user's account broken; being able to generate a user token allows an application to silently impersonate a user to other applications without consent.
{quote}

In the [public thread|https://developer.atlassian.com/display/CROWDDEV/Crowd+REST+Resources?focusedCommentId=25395404#comment-25395404] on this topic as it relates to validate-password, a Feature Request was suggested.

I have the following code:

{noformat}
protected final G getGroupCreateIfNecessary(String groupName) throws Exception
    {
        G group = getGroup(groupName);
        if (group == null)
        {
            try {
                group = createGroup(groupName);
            } catch(InvalidGroupException ige) {
                logger.debug("Turns out the group {} did already exist but was cached. Moving along");
                group = getGroup(groupName);
            }
            logger.info("'{}' group created", groupName);
        }
        return group;
    }
{noformat}

This function should never return null but it does. I think what is happening is that embedded crowd is caching the call to getGroup (so returns null) but the createGroup function goes through the cache and notices that the group exists.

Request: After you call createGroup and it notices that the group does exist, it should update the cache. That way I could use this function instead:

{noformat}
protected final G getGroupCreateIfNecessary(String groupName) throws Exception
    {
        G group;
        try {
            group = createGroup(groupName);
            logger.info("'{}' group created", groupName);
        } catch(InvalidGroupException ige) {
            logger.debug("Turns out the group {} did already exist but was cached. Moving along");
            group = getGroup(groupName);
        }
        return checkNotNull(group);
    }
{noformat}

BTW getGroup and createGroup map to getGroup and addGroup from the CrowdService.
